POM plots of CNC@CQDs films showed a clear fingerprint texture for CNC@CQDs film with CQDs contents of 0–30 μL (Fig. 5
                        ). The introduction of appropriate CQDs was found not to destroy the chiral fingerprint of the films, which was related to the cholesteric nanocellulose film of the chiral nematic structure [27]. However, it will interfere chiral nematic structure when CQDs content was 100 μL, and the fingerprint structure was no longer visible in the film. Confocal fluorescent microscopy was further used to confirm the fingerprint structure of CNCs and CNC@CQDs films (Fig. 6
                        ). As is well known, the periodicity in the refractive index normal to the axis of the helicoidal arrangement causes chiral nematic films to display distinctive fingerprint patterns under optical microscopy [28] (Fig. 6a). However, there was no fluorescence effect when the excitation wavelength was 400 nm. CNC@CQDs film (30 μL) still exhibited part of the fingerprint structure, which was consistent with results from POM diagrams (Fig. 6b). Furthermore, CNC@CQDs film (30 μL) had a fluorescence effect, which was due to reflection of blue light by the chiral nematic film in birefringence mode and consistent with the optical emission spectrum. Meanwhile, CNC@CQDs films at different angles revealed that the films appeared differently polarized at different angles (Fig. 6c and d). From a positive view of the chiral CNC film, it was basically transparent and did not reflect light. When the angle was not vertical, there was blue polarity light, which was congruent with the reflection seen in Fig. 4a. It also counterfeit-proofing the reflection of CNC@CQDs films to blue light in the POM spectrum.

In addition, the prepared CNC@CQDs films demonstrated enhanced mechanical performance with CQDs addition. The stress-strain behavior of CNCs and CNC@CQDs films showed that CNC@CQDs film (15 μL) the breaking strength increased rapidly to 65.5 MPa (Fig. 8
                        a). According to formula E = σ/ε, the Young's modulus was 4.6 GPa, tensile strength of CNC@CQDs film (30 μL) at 45 MPa, and Young's modulus at 2.6 GPa. The tensile strength of CNC@CQDs film (100 μL) was 19.3 MPa and Young's modulus at 0.8 GPa, showing good toughness. The strength of the composite CNCs film decreased and toughness increased with increased CQDs content. The bulk density of the composite film rose when CQDs were added to the CNCs system, causing a reduction in stress under external tensile tension [31]. In addition, CNCs were able to effectively enhance the substrate by forming strong interactions between adjacent whiskers due to their high specific surface area. This was from agglomeration which formed structures by hydrogen (H)-bonding and van der Waals forces to some extent [32]. With increased CQDs concentration, interactions and H-bonding structures were generated on CNCs and CQDs surfaces, resulting in enhanced toughness of the produced nanocellulose paper (Fig. 9
                        ). When stresses were generated, CNCs aggregates moved as a whole, thus preventing the macromolecules from sliding against each other [16]. As deformation increased, intercrystalline interactions were overcome. Furthermore, CQDs softened the strong mechanical properties of individual nanocrystalline rods, making the chiral films highly flexible [33]. The flexibility of these films became softer with increased CQDs content. Bending photos of CNC@CQDs films showed that, with increased CQDs, film flexibility gradually increased and the degree of bending also gradually increased and, thus, less prone to cracking under moderate bending (Fig. 8d). These chiral films could even be curled on a pen holder with a diameter of 1 cm (Fig. 8b), a curvature of 2 × 102. When bending deformation occurred, strong interfacial bonding between CQDs and adjacent CNCs allowed reorientation and bridging between fiber structures, which could dissipate excessive mechanical energy [34]. The original state was restored after being relaxed for a while (Fig. 8c). This solved the problem that nanocellulose films being brittle and easily broken.
